SIMPLE: lust
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lust
<hw>Lust</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>lust</ets>,
<ets>lust</ets>, pleasure, longing; akin to OS., D., G., & Sw.
<ets>lust</ets>, Dan. & Icel. <ets>lyst</ets>, Goth <ets>lustus</ets>,
and perh. tom Skr. <ets>lush</ets> to desire, or to E. <ets>loose</ets>.
Cf. <er>List</er> to please, <er>Listless</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Pleasure.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧ Lust and
jollity.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Inclination; desire.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For little <qex>lust</qex> had she to talk of aught.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My <qex>lust</qex> to devotion is little.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Longing desire; eagerness to possess or enjoy; -- in
a had sense; <as>as, the <ex>lust</ex> of gain</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>lust</qex> of reigning.</q> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Licentious craving; a strong sexual appetite.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Hence: Virility; vigor; active power.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lust</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lust
<hw>Lust</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Lusted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Lusting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>lystan</ets>. See
<er>Lust</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf. List to choose.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To list; to like.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧ Do so if thou <xex>lust</xex>. ⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note>
<p>⟦hand⟧ In earlier usage <xex>lust</xex> was impersonal.</p>

<p><q>In the water vessel he it cast⟦br⟧
When that him <qex>luste</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have an eager, passionate, and especially an
inordinate or sinful desire, as for the gratification of the sexual
appetite or of covetousness; -- often with <ptcl>after</ptcl>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whatsoever thy soul <qex>lusteth</qex> after.</q> <rj><qau>Deut.
xii. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whosoever looketh on a woman to <qex>lust</qex> after her, hath
committed adultery with her already in his heart.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. v.
28.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The spirit that dwelleth in us <qex>lusteth</qex> to envy.</q>
<rj><qau>James iv. 5. </qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Luster</ent>⟦br⟧
